      <h2 class="text-2xl sm:text-3xl font-bold text-brand-blue mt-0 mb-4">What AC Maintenance Actually Covers</h2>

      <p>Your AC doesn't just break one day. It warns you first. Weak airflow. A rattle that wasn't there last summer. A bill that's $40 higher for no obvious reason. Then it quits, usually in August, usually when you have company over. <strong>AC maintenance</strong> is how you avoid that whole scenario. Hilo Heating and Air has handled it for Stanton homes for years — the units we check regularly almost never become emergency calls. There's a reason for that.</p>

      <h2>Why People Skip It (And Shouldn't)</h2>
      <p>Nothing's broken. So why pay someone to come look at it?</p>
      <p>That's the logic, and it's backwards. Once something's obviously broken, you've already missed the cheap window. Routine <strong>AC maintenance</strong> is what catches the $40 fix before it turns into the $800 one — a leaking refrigerant line, a capacitor on its way out, coils so caked up the unit's burning double the energy for half the cooling.</p>
      <p>Our <strong>air conditioner servicing</strong> hits everything homeowners don't think to check. Coils. Refrigerant pressure. Wiring. Thermostat accuracy. Ducts, for leaks nobody can see. Not exciting work. But it's the difference between a system that lasts eight years and one that lasts fifteen.</p>

      <h2>Timing Is Half the Battle</h2>
      <p>Most people think of AC service as a "whenever I remember" task. Wrong approach. The smart move is getting ahead of the season, not reacting to it. That's <strong>seasonal HVAC maintenance</strong> — a spring check before your unit's actually working hard, instead of a panicked July call when every company in Orange County has a three-week wait list.</p>
      <p><strong>Seasonal HVAC maintenance</strong> also means problems surface while it's still 70 degrees outside, not 105. We've had people call us in March over a minor issue and completely sidestep a breakdown in August. Small move. Big payoff.</p>

      <h2>What Actually Happens During a Visit</h2>
      <p>A tech shows up. Runs the checklist. Tells you what they found — straight talk, not a sales pitch dressed up as a diagnosis. If the system's fine, we say it's fine. We don't manufacture problems to justify the invoice. If something's borderline, we'll flag it and let you decide what to do, on your timeline, not ours.</p>

      <h2>Why Hilo Heating and Air</h2>
      <p>We built this reputation one job at a time — show up when we say we will, tell you the truth about what's wrong. Licensed. Insured. Trained to catch what most homeowners would miss completely. Single visit or standing plan, doesn't matter — we treat your system the same either way.</p>
